LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF IDAHO
Sixty-eighth Legislature First Regular Session - 2025
IN THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
HOUSE BILL NO. 295
BY EDUCATION COMMITTEE
1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO EDUCATION; AMENDING CHAPTER 12, TITLE 33, IDAHO CODE, BY THE
3 ADDITION OF A NEW SECTION 33-1204A, IDAHO CODE, TO ESTABLISH PROVISIONS
4 REGARDING THE ADMINISTRATOR LEADERSHIP APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM; AND
5 DECLARING AN EMERGENCY.
6 Be It Enacted by the Legislature of the State of Idaho:
7 SECTION 1. That Chapter 12, Title 33, Idaho Code, be, and the same is
8 hereby amended by the addition thereto of a NEW SECTION, to be known and des-
9 ignated as Section 33-1204A, Idaho Code, and to read as follows:
10 33-1204A. ADMINISTRATOR LEADERSHIP APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM. (1) An
11 individual who does not otherwise hold an administrator certificate re-
12 quired to be a school principal or superintendent may meet the standards of
13 employment for such positions or similar positions by participating in and
14 successfully completing the administrator leadership apprenticeship pro-
15 gram as an apprentice in such positions.
16 (2) To qualify for the administrator leadership apprenticeship program
17 in a school principal role, an individual shall:
18 (a) Pass a criminal history check provided for in section 33-130, Idaho
19 Code;
20 (b) Hold, at a minimum, a bachelor's degree from a regionally or nation-
21 ally accredited college or university;
22 (c) Possess a professional background that demonstrates competency in
23 at least one (1) of the following disciplines:
24 (i) Higher education;
25 (ii) Governmental service in a management or leadership role;
26 (iii) Nonprofit organization service in a management or leader-
27 ship role;
28 (iv) Private sector service in a management or leadership role;
29 (v) Military service at the officer level; or
30 (vi) Some other education-related experience;
31 (d) Be sponsored by a public school district or local education agency;
32 and
33 (e) Be enrolled in or have previously successfully completed an ad-
34 ministrator leadership program at a regionally accredited university
35 domiciled in Idaho.
36 (3) To qualify for the administrator leadership apprenticeship program
37 in a school district superintendent role, deputy superintendent role, or
38 other similar role, an individual shall:
39 (a) Pass a criminal history check provided for in section 33-130, Idaho
40 Code;
41 (b) Hold, at a minimum, a master's degree from a regionally or nation-
42 ally accredited college or university;

2
1 (c) Possess a professional background that demonstrates competency in
2 at least one (1) of the following disciplines:
3 (i) Higher education;
4 (ii) Governmental service in a management or leadership role;
5 (iii) Nonprofit organization service in a management or leader-
6 ship role;
7 (iv) Private sector service in a management or leadership role;
8 (v) Military service at the officer level; or
9 (vi) Some other education-related experience;
10 (d) Be sponsored by a public school district or local education agency;
11 and
12 (e) Be enrolled in or have previously successfully completed a superin-
13 tendent leadership program at a regionally accredited university domi-
14 ciled in Idaho.
15 (4) An individual who is offered employment in a position by a school
16 district in a school principal role, school district superintendent role,
17 or other similar role as an apprentice for three (3) consecutive years shall
18 be eligible to receive the same certificate as the certificate of others who
19 are employed in the same role as long as such individual continues to comply
20 with the applicable requirements set forth in this section and with all other
21 applicable laws.
22 (5) An individual who successfully completes the administrator leader-
23 ship apprenticeship program and earns an administrator certificate shall be
24 subject to ongoing review.
25 SECTION 2. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
26 declared to exist, this act shall be in full force and effect on and after its
27 passage and approval.

